neering at Prairie View.

ATLANTA - A u. S. Federal
Court has said, for the first
time, that professional associa-
tions, which participate in selec-
ton of state officials, may not
discriminate against Negroes.


Judge Frank A. Hooper ruled
that Georgia's Northern District
Dental Society must accept mem
bership of DR.. Roy Bell. At
lanta dentist.


DR.. Bell was represented by
attorneys of the NAACP Legal
Defense and Educational Fund
who successfully argued that the
all-white society is Significant
ly involved with government"


Judge Hooper agreed saying
"the Georgia Legislature. by Civ
ing to the Dental ASS ociation the
right to nominate members of
three state agencies. made 1t an
agency of the State of Georgia..


1.-THE Dental Association, by
excluding Negro dentists from its
membership, thereby deprived
them of the right to vote in con-
nection with the nomination of
dentists to fill places on...three
boards Judge Hooper contin-
ued.


Zone of these boards" the
court added, has "the RESPONSE
bility of examining applicants for
a license to practice dentistry in
Georgia."


BY being denied membership
in the Northern District Dental
Society, DR.. Bell was automatic
ally denied membership inCeor-
gia Dental Association and there
by automatically denied member
ship in the National Dental AS
Sociation.


Thus, he and other Negro den
fists in his area, we're denied
opportunities for post graduate
seminars, conferences, litera-
ture and profes onal association
necessary to keep abreast of new
trends in dentistry.


The Northern District Dental
Society and the Georgia Dental
Association plan an appeal.


Jack Greenberg, director
counsel of the Fund and James
M. Nabrit, III, assistant coun-
sci, we're Of counsel.
